{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014WfQqBduazzMprgmArx5Bx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the actual log format:\n\n1. **text_delta events**: `{\"type\":\"stream_event\",\"event\":{\"type\":\"content_block_delta\",\"index\":1,\"delta\":{\"type\":\"text_delta\",\"text\":\"...\"}}}` - these are the individual tokens being streamed\n2. **assistant events**: `{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"message\":{\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"...\"}]}}` - these are complete messages\n3. **result events**: `{\"type\":\"result\",\"subtype\":\"success\",\"result\":\"...\"}` - final result\n\nThe current jq filter in the code is:\n\n\nFiltering for stream events with content_block_delta type and extracting the text from the delta object...\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing myself on the path. The delta structure is `{\"type\":\"text_delta\",\"text\":\"我\"}`, so `.event.delta.text` should definitely work to get the actual text content.\n\nBut wait—the filter might also be matching `thinking_delta` events, which have a `thinking` field instead of `text`. The `// empty` operator would filter those out since `.event.delta.text` would be null for those events.\n\nSo the jq filter should be working correctly. The real issue might be elsewhere—maybe the log file doesn't have enough lines, or the extraction isn't capturing what I expect.\n\nLet me trace through the logic: `tail -100` gets the last 100 lines, `jq` filters for `content_block_delta` events and extracts their text, then `grep -v '^$'` removes empty lines, `tail -6` keeps the last 6 text chunks, and `tr '\\n' ' '` joins them into a single line.\n\nThe problem is that each text_delta is only 1-3 characters, so even combining the last 6 gives a very short snippet that might not be meaningful. I notice there's also an `assistant` event type that contains the full accumulated message text, which would be much more useful than these tiny fragments.\n\nLet me look back at what the user actually reported about the issue. 纯文本设计的，但现在日志是 stream-json 格式，每行都是 JSON。看代码，进度报告器（199-203 行）确实有 jq 解析，所以用户描述的 bug 可能是基于旧版本，当前代码已经部分修复了。\n\n这个 jq 过滤器在提取 `content_block_delta` 事件中的文本，但问题可能是单个文本片段太小，或者 `assistant` 和 `result` 事件包含更有用的信息。\n\n用户要求改进：用 `assistant` 事件获取完整累积的文本，加上 `result` 事件，改用字节偏移量去重而不是行数，并截断到 200 字符。\n\n我需要修改脚本来追踪字节位置，从多个事件类型提取文本，并应用这些改进。\n\n关键是用 `tail -c` 从上次保存的字节位置之后读取新内容，然后通过 jq 解析每一行 JSON，跳过任何解析失败的行。\n\n实际上，更简单的方法是每次都读取完整日志，而不是尝试只读新内容——这样可以避免在行中间切割的问题。\n\n我可以用字节计数来检查是否有新内容，但仍然读取整个文件来提取文本。\n\n现在我在写一个脚本来检查字节数是否有变化，如果有变化就更新计数，然后用 jq 过滤器来提取最有用的信息——优先查找 `assistant` 类型的事件，因为它们包含完整的累积文本。\n\nWriting jq filter... Refining the extraction logic...\n\nI need to handle the different event types properly - pulling text from `content_block_delta` events, falling back to the `result` field if available, then taking just the last 200 characters of the combined output to keep the snippet concise. I'm working through how to extract text from different event types in the log file. The `assistant` events contain accumulated content with both text and thinking blocks, so I need to filter for just the text type. Since `--include-partial-messages` produces multiple assistant events, the last one would have the most complete message. I'm thinking the cleanest approach is to use jq to process the tail of the log, extracting text from the appropriate event types and getting the final snippet. I'm realizing the streaming events have a clear structure: `text_delta` fragments come through during streaming, then a complete `assistant` event appears once the message finishes, and finally a `result` event at the very end. For the progress reporter, I should extract the streaming text deltas to show what's currently being generated, and fall back to the last completed assistant message if needed, keeping just the final 200 characters to stay concise.\n\nThe bash approach needs refinement though—I want the most recent