ng the same content twice. I need to decide whether to pull from only the streaming deltas, only the final assistant message, or handle the result event differently to avoid this redundancy.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to prioritize based on what's available: use the result event if the task is complete, fall back to the last assistant event's text, and only use text_delta fragments if neither of those exist. Let me refactor the jq logic to check for the result event first...\n\nRefining the extraction logic... I'm realizing the jq slice syntax might not be compatible across all versions, so I should switch to bash string manipulation instead. Let me refactor this to extract the text using jq but handle the truncation in bash, and I'll also consider using byte offsets to avoid duplicate entries in the log.\n\nNow I'm setting up the progress reporter loop that checks the tmux session and monitors the log file size to only report when there's new content...\n\nContinuing with the log parsing logic...\n\nI'm extracting the readable text from the stream-json log by checking for result events first, then falling back to assistant messages or text delta fragments if needed, and finally truncating the output to the last 200 characters for the log snippet.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the notification format the user wants—a two-line message with the task progress and the latest output excerpt, and I need to verify whether the `openclaw system event` command can handle newlines in the `--text` parameter.\n\nI'll use bash's `$'\\n'` syntax to safely embed a literal newline, then construct the event text with the task ID, elapsed time, and the last 100 characters of the log output.\n\nAfter that, I need to update the claude-spawn.sh file to replace the relevant section, and then make corresponding changes to SKILL.md—updating the dedup description and the version notes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_to